like, two-thirds

32:06.525 --> 32:13.465 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to one-third to join it. But
ever since Margaret
Thatcher demanded her money
back, John Major

32:13.565 --> 32:19.604 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
had lots of trouble with the
Conservative
Party angry about Brussels,
angry about what

32:19.704 --> 32:22.240 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
they perceived to be loss of
sovereignty.

32:22.340 --> 32:28.747 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And to manage his own party,
David Cameron
thought he should promise them
this referendum,

32:28.847 --> 32:34.052 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this in-or-out referendum on
Brussels, if
he won power again. Well, lo and
behold, even

32:34.152 --> 32:40.625 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
to his surprise, he won a
majority, so he
sort of caught himself and felt
that he had

32:40.725 --> 32:44.563 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to make good on his promise and
hold this
in-or-out referendum.

32:44.663 --> 32:50.402 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So what are the
main arguments
today for leaving the E.U.?

32:50.502 --> 32:55.740 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEVEN ERLANGER: Well, some of
them are historical
and nostalgic. Britain is an
island that was

32:55.841 --> 33:02.280 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
an empire. It's never been fully
European,
but it's too close to Europe to
escape it,

33:02.380 --> 33:11.223 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
too.
It was very much engaged in the
great European
wars, but it won them, and so it
has a different

33:11.323 --> 33:17.329 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
sense of its own sovereignty
than, let's say,
France or Germany, or Belgium,
which understand

33:17.429 --> 33:20.232 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
that sovereignty can be
vulnerable.

33:20.332 --> 33:28.840 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And Britain isn't -- it's an
Anglo-Saxon country.
It has a different notion of
laws. It's not

33:28.940 --> 33:35.213 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the Napoleonic code. So that's
one thing.
And the second thing is the
British sense

33:35.313 --> 33:40.552 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
of sovereignty. They feel
Parliament really
must be sovereign, and the
people who want

33:40.652 --> 33:47.292 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
to leave feel Brussels
interferes too much
in the operations of British
laws and British

33:47.392 --> 33:49.060 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
justice.

33:49.160 --> 33:53.665 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the third major issue, which
is an odd
one, really, is immigration,
because when

33:53.765 --> 34:01.172 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you're part of the E.U., you
have to guarantee
freedom of movement and freedom
of working

34:01.273 --> 34:05.543 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for every citizen of the E.U. So
they're worried
about their jobs.

34:05.644 --> 34:11.082 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, quickly, what
are the main
arguments in the other direction
that Britain

34:11.182 --> 34:13.151 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
should stay in, and who's making
them?

34:13.251 --> 34:19.457 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEVEN ERLANGER: Well, the main
lessons are,
Britain is part of Europe, it's
inescapable,

34:19.557 --> 34:21.259 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
even the wars show that.

34:21.359 --> 34:27.165 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Britain's security is guaranteed
by being
part of this larger group.
Britain's trade

34:27.265 --> 34:34.306 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is heavily toward the European
Union. At least
a million Britons also take
advantage of this

34:34.406 --> 34:40.412 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
freedom of movement and freedom
of labor and
live inside Europe. And the city
of London,

34:40.512 --> 34:46.351 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
which is a big financial center,
benefits
more from being inside the E.U.
than not.

34:46.451 --> 34:50.755 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are a lot of companies who
are based
in Britain because they want to
be part of

34:50.855 --> 34:57.162 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the E.U., but also favor British
labor laws.
So, if Britain leaves, the great
worry is

34:57.262 --> 35:03.068 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
some of those companies will
leave, that there
will be capital flight, that
Britain's security

35:03.168 --> 35:07.739 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
will be diminished. And, also,
the Americans
have been very clear about
wanting Britain

35:07.839 --> 35:09.674 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to stay in.

35:09.774 --> 35:14.179 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And that's
exactly what I wanted
to pick up on. What is it felt
is the U.S.'

35:14.279 --> 35:15.513 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
stake in all this?

35:15.613 --> 35:18.984 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEVEN ERLANGER: Well, the U.S.
is not being
altruistic.

35:19.084 --> 35:25.290 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The U.S. sees Britain as a great
ally, and
it wants its great ally inside
the European

35:25.390 --> 35:32.430 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Union, which has a big effect,
frankly, on
global trade regulations, on
data privacy

35:32.530 --> 35:38.169 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
regulations. And the U.S. feels,
with its
ally Britain, it has more
influence inside

35:38.269 --> 35:41.072 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the European Union than it would
otherwise.

35:41.172 --> 35:46.244 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, also, Britain is a big
military power
with France, and it's good to
have Britain

35:46.344 --> 35:50.348 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
not just inside NATO, but inside
the European
Union itself.

35:50.448 --> 35:54.652 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, I guess
you're looking
for a lively debate for the next
four months.

35:54.753 --> 36:00.091 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEVEN ERLANGER: Well, it's
going to be lively,
partly because what's added
spice is, now

36:00.191 --> 36:06.131 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the Conservative leadership is
at stake, because
Boris Johnson, the mayor of
London, who's

36:06.231 --> 36:11.903 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
always considered slightly
buffoonish, but
also very popular and a possible
prime minister,

36:12.003 --> 36:18.510 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
has broken with David Cameron,
and is favoring
exit, while Cameron wants to
stay inside.

36:18.610 --> 36:24.149 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And Cameron's quite angry with
Johnson, but
Johnson, I think, sees it as his
best chance

36:24.249 --> 36:27.252 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of becoming prime minister down
the road.

36:27.352 --> 36:30.188 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Drama at every
level.

36:30.288 --> 36:32.290 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Steven Erlanger with The New
York Times, we
thank you.

36:32.390 --> 36:35.960 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
STEVEN ERLANGER: Thank you.

36:36.061 --> 36:48.540 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now: big hopes in
the fight
against cancer and the potential
for some

36:48.640 --> 36:51.543 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
surprising allies: elephants.

36:51.643 --> 36:56.748 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Special correspondent Jackie
Judd reports
on researchers thinking outside
the box.

36:56.848 --> 37:05.590 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN: The Ringling Bros. and
Barnum &amp; Bailey
performing pachyderms!

37:05.690 --> 37:11.963 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACKIE JUDD: This spring, all of
these circus
elephants will be permanently
retired. But

37:12.063 --> 37:18.203 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
as they leave the center ring,
they are taking
center stage in another unlikely
place, the

37:18.303 --> 37:21.206 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Huntsman Cancer Institute in
Salt Lake City.

37:21.306 --> 37:24.676 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. JOSHUA SCHIFFMAN, Huntsman
Cancer Institute:
Just about every person I met
who heard about

37:24.776 --> 37:29.481 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
this would come up and ask,
elephants, cancer,
what's the connection?

37:29.581 --> 37:38.323 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JACKIE JUDD: The possible
connection is a
work in progress, led by
pediatric oncologist

37:38.423 --> 37:40.225 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Dr. Joshua Schiffman.

37:40.325 --> 37:42.227 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOMAN: Insert the needle into
the vein.

37:42.327 --> 37:47.031 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACKIE JUDD: He has enlisted the
support of
the Ringling Bros. Center for
Elephant Conservation

37:47.132 --> 37:52.937 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in Florida and the Hogle Zoo in
Salt Lake
to draw blood from these sturdy
mammals for

37:53.037 --> 37:54.806 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
his experiments.

37:54.906 --> 38:00.945 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Logically, elephants should get
cancer far
more often than we do. They have
100 times

38:01.045 --> 38:07.352 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
the cells than humans,
therefore, much more
opportunity for those cells to
mutate into

38:07.452 --> 38:12.891 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
cancer. But that's not the case.
Less than
5 percent of elephant deaths are
attributed

38:12.991 --> 38:14.826 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to cancer.

38:14.926 --> 38:20.932 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. JOSHUA SCHIFFMAN: Elephants
have had 55
million years of evolution to
figure out how

38:21.032 --> 38:26.804 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to avoid cancer. Now it's our
turn to take
a page out of nature's playbook,
and try to

38:26.905 --> 38:31.109 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
figure out, how do we help our
patients and
families with cancer?

38:31.209 --> 38:38.383 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACKIE JUDD: Most humans have
two copies of
a gene called p53. When
everything is working,

38:38.483 --> 38:44.822 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
the protein in p53 is a
cancer-suppressor,
repairing or killing mutant
cells so they

38:44.923 --> 38:49.694 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
don't multiply. Elephants have
40 copies of
p53.

38:49.794 --> 38:55.433 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. JOSHUA SCHIFFMAN: This is
our tissue culture
room. This is where we actually
do the experiments

38:55.533 --> 39:03.007 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to try to understand, how does
elephant p53
work? In here are the actual
cells growing.

39:03.107 --> 39:08.513 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACKIE JUDD: After bombarding
elephant blood
with radiation, Dr. Schiffman
and his team

39:08.613 --> 39:16.421 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
stood back and observed how the
elephant p53
responded to the damaged cells.
The answer,

39:16.521 --> 39:20.725 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
recently published in "The
Journal of the
American Medical Association,"
was that the

39:20.825 --> 39:26.531 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
multiple genes responded far
more robustly
than p53's response in humans.

39:26.631 --> 39:33.638 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. JOSHUA SCHIFFMAN: Instead of
trying to
repair themselves, the elephant
cells, many

39:33.738 --> 39:39.744 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of them, all went on to cell
death, to this
cell suicide, or what we call
apoptosis.

39:39.844 --> 39:43.781 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's as if these elephant cells
have said,
well, it's much safer, much
better strategy

39:43.881 --> 39:49.988 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to just kill the cell and start
over. If we
do that, there's no way that
that cell can

39:50.088 --> 39:55.760 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
go on to become cancer, and that
was an aha
moment for us in the lab. We're
trying to

39:55.860 --> 40:00.298 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
learn how to get kids better
with cancer without
making them sick.

40:00.398 --> 40:06.638 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACKIE JUDD: Now the research
has turned to
this question: How does elephant
p53 respond

40:06.738 --> 40:13.177 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in human cancer cells? And could
it stop the
disease cold? Could it be a
treatment to prevent

40:13.278 --> 40:15.213 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
cancer or halt its growth?

40:15.313 --> 40:21.286 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. JOSHUA SCHIFFMAN: In here
are three breast
cancers from different
individuals that have

40:21.386 --> 40:28.326 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
been growing in the labs. And we
take the
elephant p53 and transfect it.
We put it into

40:28.426 --> 40:35.566 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the breast cancer cell lines,
and we wait
and we see, will the elephant
p53 kill these

40:35.667 --> 40:39.470 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
breast cancer cells?

40:39.570 --> 40:46.911 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACKIE JUDD: The research, and
where it may
lead, would be especially
meaningful for people

40:47.011 --> 40:54.018 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
like Tony Means. He and others
with a genetic
disorder called Li-Fraumeni
Syndrome have

40:54.118 --> 41:01.225 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
only one p53 gene, instead of
two, leaving
them virtually defenseless
against cancer.

41:01.326 --> 41:06.164 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In your family, your mother had
Li-Fraumeni,
died very young.

41:06.264 --> 41:07.865 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
TONY MEANS, Cancer Patient: Yes,
ma'am.

41:07.965 --> 41:12.737 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACKIE JUDD: You have aunts and
uncles who
have cancer and have
Li-Fraumeni.

41:12.837 --> 41:15.907 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TONY MEANS: Yes, a good chunk of
our family.
I would say a majority,

41:16.007 --> 41:18.476 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JACKIE JUDD: And they have all
been tested?
They have...

41:18.576 --> 41:19.777 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

41:19.877 --> 41:21.779 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TONY MEANS: Well, every single
one has been
Li-Fraumeni.

41:21.879 --> 41:26.084 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACKIE JUDD: Means is being
treated for cancer
and 6-year-old daughter Emma is
being watched

41:26.184 --> 41:31.889 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
by Dr. Schiffman because of a
small brain
tumor. Two other children with
Li-Fraumeni

41:31.989 --> 41:37.562 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are frequently screened, and the
family takes
part in Dr. Schiffman's research
in any way

41:37.662 --> 41:39.430 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
they can.

41:39.530 --> 41:43.434 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TONY MEANS: I have kind of put
hope in him
by choosing to have children,
knowing that

41:43.534 --> 41:45.670 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
there's a chance they could have
the gene.

41:45.770 --> 41:48.773 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JACKIE JUDD: But you understand
this is years
off, if ever.

41:48.873 --> 41:50.775 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
TONY MEANS: Oh, yes, yes.

41:50.875 --> 41:52.377 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JACKIE JUDD: If ever.

41:52.477 --> 41:55.947 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
TONY MEANS: Oh, yes, yes, yes,
yes. Who knows?

41:56.047 --> 42:02.120 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACKIE JUDD: And that is where
Avi Schroeder
comes in. Dr. Schroeder of
Technion, the Israel

42:02.220 --> 42:07.625 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Institute of Technology, joined
the research
several months ago, with the
goal of developing

42:07.725 --> 42:12.296 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a drug for humans that would
mimic the elephant's
robust p53.

42:12.397 --> 42:17.769 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AVI SCHROEDER, Technion: Now
there's a delivery
issue. How can we get that
protein to the

42:17.869 --> 42:24.008 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
disease site, into the cancer
cells, to act
and to perform the therapeutic
activity on

42:24.108 --> 42:29.414 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
site? We're going to wrap the
proteins inside
a nanoparticle, and they will
release the

42:29.514 --> 42:31.215 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
protein inside the cancer cells.

42:31.315 --> 42:34.952 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JACKIE JUDD: And if everything
works, the
cancer cell will be killed?

42:35.052 --> 42:40.091 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AVI SCHROEDER: Yes, the cancer
cell will go
into a death cycle after that,
yes.

42:40.191 --> 42:43.261 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN: We are excited to have Dr.
Schroeder
here.

42:43.361 --> 42:49.967 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JACKIE JUDD: The team of
optimists believes
clinical trials could begin in
three years.

42:50.067 --> 42:55.773 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Not surprisingly, there is
skepticism in the
medical community, and that is
shared by Dr.

42:55.873 --> 42:59.377 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Lee Helman, the head of clinical
research
at the National Cancer
Institute.

42:59.477 --> 43:05.049 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. LEE HELMAN, National Cancer
Institute:
The whole idea of putting an
elephant gene

43:05.149 --> 43:09.987 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that's regulated in a unique way
into a human
being, when we have had enough
trouble putting

43:10.087 --> 43:14.792 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
human genes into human beings
with all kinds
of difficulty, I would say he
has got a lot

43:14.892 --> 43:16.694 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of hurdles to overcome.

43:16.794 --> 43:23.100 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACKIE JUDD: But Dr. Helman does
believe there
is value to this deeper
investigation into

43:23.201 --> 43:25.002 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
p53.

43:25.102 --> 43:31.108 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. LEE HELMAN: I think his
finding only lends
further evidence to support that
hypothesis

43:31.209 --> 43:36.948 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
that p53 function, and
understanding it and
being able to regulate it, would
be a major

43:37.048 --> 43:40.151 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
step forward in our ability to
treat cancer.

43:40.251 --> 43:45.890 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JACKIE JUDD: Cancer touches
almost every family,
directly or indirectly. For
families like

43:45.990 --> 43:47.658 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the Means, it is a certainty.

43:47.758 --> 43:53.431 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, what is happening in this
lab, at this
zoo, could be life- changing.

43:53.531 --> 43:56.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Have you taken the kids to the
zoo to see
the elephants?

43:56.501 --> 44:00.738 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TONY MEANS: Yes. Oh, man, that
was awesome.
The kids loved it, and it was
kind of fun

44:00.838 --> 44:06.010 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for me to sit there as a father
and just look
at them. This is the answer in
their lifetime.

44:06.110 --> 44:09.881 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's all I want is for my kids
to have that.
And this -- this gives them
hope.

44:09.981 --> 44:14.218 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. JOSHUA SCHIFFMAN: I don't
promise my patients
it will happen, because I don't
want to have

44:14.318 --> 44:20.391 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
them disappointed. But if I
didn't believe
