45:16.314 --> 45:26.891 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARTIN ESPADA, "Vivas to Those
Who Have Failed":
He lived many lives. And he
evolved from someone

45:26.991 --> 45:32.897 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who was working in the streets
of East New
York, where I grew up, to
someone who was

45:32.997 --> 45:37.535 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
documenting the condition of an
entire people.

45:37.635 --> 45:40.404 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: What's it like
seeing your
father's work in the
Smithsonian?

45:40.504 --> 45:42.273 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARTIN ESPADA: Surreal.

45:42.373 --> 45:46.444 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Martin Espada,
Frank's son,
is an award-winning poet, a
former tenant

45:46.544 --> 45:50.815 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
lawyer, and longtime professor
at the University
of Massachusetts.

45:50.915 --> 45:55.853 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
His new volume, "Vivas to Those
Who Have Failed"
-- the title comes from a line
by Walt Whitman

45:55.953 --> 45:59.624 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
-- is filled with poems that
remember and
celebrate his father.

45:59.724 --> 46:08.332 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MARTIN ESPADA: "I am the
archaeologist. I
sift the shards of you,
cufflinks, passports

46:08.432 --> 46:14.739 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
photos, a button from the March
on Washington
with a black hand shaking a
white hand, letters

46:14.839 --> 46:20.511 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
in Spanish, your birth
certificate from a
town high in the mountains."

46:20.611 --> 46:26.817 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The poetry about my father is
both elegiac
and documentary. Poets often in
these situations

46:26.917 --> 46:33.157 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
perform the function of
preachers, right?
People expect you to say
something meaningful

46:33.257 --> 46:38.429 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in this age where language has
become divorced
from meaning and we live in a
time of hyper-euphemism.

46:38.529 --> 46:43.734 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: But you're a
storyteller. You
have got this public role as a
poet, but most

46:43.834 --> 46:45.903 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of all, at that moment, you're a
son.

46:46.003 --> 46:49.807 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARTIN ESPADA: Yes, first and
foremost, and
I was feeling that as a son.

46:49.907 --> 46:56.380 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's an undercurrent of
loss, of grief,
and grappling with grief, and
trying to see

46:56.480 --> 47:01.819 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the ways in which poetry might
be able to
heal grief, if not for me, then
for somebody

47:01.919 --> 47:03.688 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
else.

47:03.788 --> 47:07.124 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: In his poems,
Martin refers
back to old home movies that
show his father,

47:07.224 --> 47:12.930 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a man who'd come to New York
from Puerto Rico
as a boy in 1939, and was an
athlete who played

47:13.030 --> 47:14.965 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
semi-pro baseball.

47:15.066 --> 47:20.171 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
While serving in the Air Force
in 1949, he
was jailed for a week in
Mississippi for not

47:20.271 --> 47:21.505 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
