47:29.680 --> 47:32.650 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Frank Espada
would become a
community organizer. He founded
East New York

47:32.750 --> 47:36.687 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Action in the early 1960s, and
worked in the
civil rights movement.

47:36.787 --> 47:41.692 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARTIN ESPADA: There's little
attention paid,
up to this point, to what we
might call the

47:41.792 --> 47:43.527 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Latino civil rights movement.

47:43.627 --> 47:47.398 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Above all, says
Martin, who
sometimes worked with his
father, he was an

47:47.498 --> 47:54.171 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
artist who documented what he
saw. Frank Espada
published a book in 2006 titled
"The Puerto

47:54.271 --> 47:58.909 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Rican Diaspora: Themes in the
Survival of
a People," and his photographic
work has been

47:59.009 --> 48:03.481 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
